metadata.name: Charcoal Brutalism #49
metadata.description:
Based on a similar technique as "Charcoal Landscapes", using lines limited to 8 possible directions, this work is about the repetition of patterns at different scales and the use of negative spaces.
The texture created from the noise combined with the structures that emerges from this algorithm create a look similar to the brutalist architecture of the last century.

There are 10 scale variations but with almost infinite possible outcomes.
Inverted colours have a small chance of dropping.

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: Entropy Blender #75
metadata.description:
This is about a word that doesn't exist and it's exactly what the heart wants to scream. The message you dance, the story you hope the skin delivers.

Image composition made of CGA generated with Sims 4 inputs and blended with PureSpider template.

metadata.name: Oyoyiz #283
metadata.description:
Oyoyiz is an abstract composition generator. Available in 8 different color palettes and 2 styles (Organic and Brutalist), shapes made of a random number of segments are displayed on a grid. The name Oyoyiz was randomly generated.

Coded with Processing and P5js in October 2022 by @eltono and Michel - www.eltono.com

metadata.name: I AM UNFOLDING #312
metadata.description:
In the past, I was but fragments
Rough and jagged
Indefinitely, I weathered and grew
A sculpture formed, unstructured

In the present, I am the precipice
A grandiose monolith
My angles sharp, my lines precise
A work of art, restructured

The future looms before
A blank formlessness yet to be
My function undefined
In perpetuity, unfolding

-----------------------------------------

Best efforts have been made to optimize this project; however, for best performance, a machine with a dedicated GPU is recommended. Viewing the project in live mode is also recommended.

S - export a high resolution image.
P - pause the animation.

metadata.name: The Past Ahead #99
metadata.description:
Cyanotypes once were the most advanced technology to create images. When I see one today I look at it as a beautiful relic and I can't help but put my present in perspective. In these uncertain times the technologies we use to create are threatened with sudden extinction. But I feel joy in imagining our works joining the strata of history, a fallen species, the breeding ground of creations to come.

Controls :

• Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

———————

The Past Ahead by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity

metadata.name: Anachronous #141
metadata.description:
This project is about the exploration of chaotic structures created with lines and blurry silhouettes. They work together to make the shapes emerge without revealing them completely and create dark and light areas that compose a feeling of depth and weight to the scene.

Some pieces are chaotic, some more ordered. Some have strong compositions, some don't. By zooming in on the details we can let our mind wander and start seeing shapes.

Best experienced in full-screen.

Press S to take a screenshot
Press M to take a high resolution screenshot
Press H to take a higher resolution screenshot (may not work for some devices)

WARNING: Project is using webgl, it may not work on some older devices.

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: Bloomside of The Past Field #31
metadata.description:
Made this work as a part of trying to make misprint effects, while maintaining the square form.
The scene are the flowers and other vegetations. Sometimes the scene will have the rain, snow and other weathers.

I imagined the scene was a form of painting, drawing or pictures on the postcard. So, all of them will have been signed as a loved sign, dusted sign (the spiders will come) and left unsigned. 

-----
The grain function which I used from Gorilla Sun Fx(text)
written in p5js. 
-----
my friends are married and getting married. I was left and I'm growing the flowers for myself in the sideline of the park, house, or elsewhere.

metadata.name: Concrete #340
metadata.description:
640 unique sketches of imaginary walls, inspired by the work of Norwegian architect Erling Viksjø (1910–1971) and his artist collaborators. Viksjø designed the Government Quarter in Oslo and invited artists from different disciplines to help design the facades and interiors of the buildings.

Viksjø’s aim was to “soften” modernist architecture. He invented «Natural Concrete», a type of concrete that deliberately exposes the mixed-in stones on its surface to give it warmth and a human touch. In my work, I have similar ambitions—using code instead of concrete.

The different styles of the piece are inspired by, and dedicated to some of the artists who worked together with Viksjø: Jakob Weidemann (~2%), Carl Nesjar (~18%), Odd Tandberg (~30%), and Tore Haaland (~50%).

In live mode, press ‘S’ to save an image at current resolution or ‘P’ to save a high-resolution file at 6000×6000px (this might take a while depending on your hardware).

Original artwork by Andreas Rau · Made with p5.js & glsl · Oslo, 2021
